<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    SayzoHud.app — nested helper bundle inside Sayzo.app/Contents/Frameworks/.

    Why this exists (the Helper.app pattern, v3.2.0)
    ================================================
    The HUD subprocess (PySide6 + QtWebEngine) needs its own
    LaunchServices ASN + Core Graphics System (window server)
    connection or windows don't render. macOS treats child processes
    of the same .app bundle as "internal helpers" and refuses to
    register them as independent UI apps — so spawning the main
    sayzo-agent binary from the agent (also sayzo-agent) yields a
    HUD with bundleID=[NULL] / !cgsConnection in lsappinfo.

    The canonical fix used by Chrome, Electron, Slack, every
    multi-process Mac app: nest a separate .app bundle inside
    Frameworks/ with a DIFFERENT CFBundleIdentifier. macOS then
    treats the helper as a fully separate app — own ASN, own CGS
    connection, windows render correctly.

    This bundle's MacOS/SayzoHud is a tiny C wrapper (compiled from
    installer/macos/sayzo_hud_wrapper.c). The wrapper posix_spawns
    /Applications/Sayzo.app/Contents/MacOS/sayzo-agent hud --idle
    (the real PyInstaller binary, which has all the Python+Qt data)
    and waits for it. Stdin/stdout flow through naturally via FD
    inheritance, so the agent's existing async pipe machinery in
    gui/hud/launcher.py works unchanged.

    Why the wrapper isn't just a symlink to sayzo-agent
    ===================================================
    PyInstaller's bootloader uses _NSGetExecutablePath() to find
    its bundled _internal/ data. If we symlinked/copied the main
    binary into MacOS/SayzoHud, the bootloader would look for data
    inside SayzoHud.app/Contents/Frameworks/ — which is empty —
    and fail. The wrapper avoids this by being a tiny native
    program that doesn't init Cocoa; the actual PyInstaller bundle
    runs in the spawned child whose binary path resolves data
    correctly.

    LSUIElement vs LSBackgroundOnly
    ===============================
    LSUIElement=YES — same as the parent agent. The HUD subprocess
    has visible NSWindows (the actual UI overlay) but no Dock icon
    and no menu bar. LSBackgroundOnly is intentionally absent: setting
    it would block the HUD's NSWindows from being visible per the
    same logic that bit us in the parent's Info.plist (see
    sayzo-agent.spec note about LSBackgroundOnly being implicit when
    console=True).
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>CFBundleDevelopmentRegion</key>
    <string>en</string>

    <key>CFBundleDisplayName</key>
    <string>Sayzo HUD</string>

    <key>CFBundleExecutable</key>
    <string>SayzoHud</string>

    <key>CFBundleIdentifier</key>
    <string>com.sayzo.agent.hud</string>

    <key>CFBundleInfoDictionaryVersion</key>
    <string>6.0</string>

    <key>CFBundleName</key>
    <string>Sayzo HUD</string>

    <key>CFBundlePackageType</key>
    <string>APPL</string>

    <key>CFBundleShortVersionString</key>
    <string>3.2.0</string>

    <key>CFBundleVersion</key>
    <string>3.2.0</string>

    <key>CFBundleSignature</key>
    <string>????</string>

    <!-- Hide from Dock — same accessory-app classification as parent. -->
    <key>LSUIElement</key>
    <true/>

    <!-- Match the parent agent's macOS floor (CoreAudio Process Taps). -->
    <key>LSMinimumSystemVersion</key>
    <string>14.4</string>

    <key>LSApplicationCategoryType</key>
    <string>public.app-category.productivity</string>
</dict>
</plist>
